Introduction:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This file is designed to give you a basic introduction to the various
"dotfiles" (configuration files whose names begin with ``.'' in your account).

In particular, when you log in, these files are read:

  .Xdefaults .alias .cshrc .fvwmrc .login .xinitrc ~/.modules/personal.mdl

This file provides an introduction to when these files are read, and what
types of customizations you might want to make to each one, and how to do so.
Each dotfile also has inline comments to help you understand more about the
file and what it's doing.  Here's an overview:

Key: [path] ~ Program which is executed
     (path) ~ Configuration file in your account which is processed
     ?text? ~ Choice which you are presented with
      Done  ~ You are now logged in and can begin working 

  [/bin/csh] 
      |
      V
  (~/.login)
      |
      V        Yes
  ? Start X ? -----> [/usr/openwin/bin/openwin]
      |                          |
      | No                       |
      V                          V              
  (~/.cshrc)                (~/.xinitrc)
      |                          |
      V                          ----> [/usr/openwin/bin/xrdb]
  modules system                                 |
      |                                          V
      V                                   (~/.Xdefaults)
  (~/.modules/personal.mdl)                      |
      |                          |<--------------|
      V                          |
    Done                         |---> [/usr/local/bin/fvwm]
                                 |               |
                                 |               V
 [/usr/openwin/bin/xterm] <------|          (~/.fvwmrc)
      |                          | 
      V                          |
   [/bin/csh]                    |
      |                    Wait for fvwm
      V                       logout 
   (~/.cshrc)
      |
      V
  modules system 
      |
      V
  (~/.modules/personal.mdl)
      |
      V
    Done


When you log in:

1. After you type your name and password, your shell (/bin/csh) is started
   as a login shell.  This causes it to first read the file: ~/.login
   in your home directory.  You should add options to .login which you want
   to effect your entire login session.

2. If you launch OpenWindows, your ~/.xinitrc script is executed.  Here you
   launch your window manager (/usr/local/bin/fvwm), which controls the
   way your windows and menus appear, and several programs to appear by
   default, including two xterms with shells in them, and an XEmacs editor.
   You should add commands to ~/.xinitrc that you want to execute when you
   begin a new OpenWindows session.

3. Your ~/.xinitrc script uses /usr/openwin/bin/xrdb to load your ~/.Xdefaults
   file, which containing resource settings for many X-based programs.
   If you want to change fonts or colors for particular programs, make those
   changes here.

4. Your ~/.xinitrc script launches your window manager (/usr/local/bin/fvwm),
   which is responsible for managing your virtual screens, displaying window
   title bars, and menus of commands which appear when you click on your
   screen background.  fvwm reads your ~/.fvwmrc file, which you can modify
   if you want to change your window colors or menu commands.

5. Your ~/.xinitrc script launches one or more xterms, each of which launches
   a separate instance of your shell (/bin/csh).  Each shell then reads the
   ~/.cshrc file, which should contain settings you want each time a new 
   shell is started.

6. Your .cshrc file invokes the 'modules' system to provide flexible account
   configuration.  man module(1) and modulefile(5) for detailed information.
   The last module to get loaded is your personal module, which is in
   ~/.modules/personal.mdl.  You should place most of your environment
   customizations in this file: Path settings, environment variables, etc.
   all belong here.

Changing Fonts in Your Account:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
From a shell, run the ``xfontsel'' program.  It will let you play around
with different font properties, and display a font string specifying what
you are currently viewing at the top of its window.  Change these lines in
your ~/.Xdefaults file:

   *font:                  lucidasanstypewriter-12
   *bodyFont:              lucidasanstypewriter-12
   *boldFont:              lucidasanstypewriter-bold-12

Now reload your resources using the "Reload Resources" command under your
rightmost mouse button.  The changes will affect subsequent shells and other
applications you start.

Changing Colors in your Account:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
From a shell, run the ``xcolorsel'' program.  It will display tiles of the
available named colors.  The default foreground and background application
can be changed by modifying these lines in your ~/.Xdefaults file:

  *foreground:            black
  *background:            gray90

Note that color names can simply be specified as one word, case-insensitive.
Now reload your resources using the "Reload Resources" command under your
rightmost mouse button.  The changes will affect subsequent shells and other
applications you start.

To change the default colors of your window title bars, you will need to
modify the color settings at the top of your ~/.fvwmrc file:

  StdForeColor            black
  StdBackColor            lightsteelblue3
  HiForeColor             black
  HiBackColor             lightsteelblue2
  StickyForeColor         black
  StickyBackColor         lightsteelblue
  MenuForeColor           black
  MenuBackColor           lightsteelblue
  MenuStippleColor        black
  PagerBackColor          gray90

After saving your changes, you can make them take effect immediately by
selecting the "Restart Fvwm" command from under your rightmost mouse button.

How To Get Help:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If you have problems or questions about your account or startup files, send
email to ``admin''.  If you have general questions about UNIX or the department,
start up the Netscape web browser (available by selecting "Netscape" from
under your leftmost mouse button) and go to: "http://localhost/"
